    public interface Monad9<T1,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T8,T9,M extends HigherKinded9<?,?,?,?,?,?,?,?,?,M>>
extends Functor9<T1,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T8,T9>, HigherKinded9<T1,T2,T3,T4,T5,T6,T7,T8,T9,M>
    Defines a 9-ary Monad by generalizing the flatMap function.

    All instances of the Monad9 interface should obey the three control laws:

    • Left identity: unit(a).flatMap(f) ≡ f a
    • Right identity: m.flatMap(unit) ≡ m
    • Associativity: m.flatMap(f).flatMap(g) ≡ m.flatMap(x -> f.apply(x).flatMap(g)
    given
    • an object m of type HigherKinded9<T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8, T9, M>
    • an object a consisting of values of type T1 ✕ T2 ✕ T3 ✕ T4 ✕ T5 ✕ T6 ✕ T7 ✕ T8 ✕ T9
    • a constructor unit taking an a and producing an object of type M
    • a function f: T1 ✕ T2 ✕ T3 ✕ T4 ✕ T5 ✕ T6 ✕ T7 ✕ T8 ✕ T9 → M
    To read further about monads in Java please refer to What's Wrong in Java 8, Part IV: Monads.
    Since:
    1.1.0
